                <div>
                    <h1>Salary</h1>

                    <p>
                        I've talked about money with my colleagues, mentees, and friends for years. Knowing how much people get paid is one of the missing steps to fixing gender-based income inequality (you can also replace gender with race and country of origin).
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Last week, <b>Dan Mall</b> blew my mind with his <a href="https://danmall.com/salary-income" target="_blank" rel="noopener">public salary and income page</a>, and just like he borrowed the idea from <b><a href="https://matthewsmith.website/salary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Matthew Smith</a></b>, I also decided to "steal like an artist".
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        A little bit of extra context. 
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        I skipped over the first few years as a professional working in <b>Portugal</b>. Like many other Portuguese millennials that started their careers around the <b><time>2008</time> crisis</b>, I spent many years working as a "fake freelancer".
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        That means that even though I had a boss and hierarchy, workplace, and working hours like any employee, I was being paid like a service provider and had to pay all taxes and social security (while illegal, this was very common among young people).
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        In <time>2014</time>, I moved to <b>Sweden</b>, where my career took off (or started to happen, depending on how you look at it). So all numbers from then on are shown in Swedish Krona (SEK).
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Sweden is quite transparent when it comes to income. All Swedish residents and organizations can request yearly financial data on anyone living here (for AB companies, that info is fully public). The catch is that the person being checked will also know who requested the financial record.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        But let's be honest, asking for a check to figure out your colleague's salary would be rude (and might lead to incorrect conclusions as salary is only one form of income).
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Also, in most European countries, salaries are paid monthly. Just multiply my values by 12 to get yearly figures ðŸ¤“
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        One last note, you might know that I have a Product Design focused <a href="https://www.youtube.com/@menosketiago" target="_blank" rel="noopener">YouTube channel</a>, but I am very far from reaching the minimum subscribers and watch time to get ad money from it.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And so far, <a href="https://www.buymeacoffee.com/menosketiago" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Buy me a coffee</a> donations have reached a whopping 15$ (no shade, I love you my oat milk latte patrons).
                    </p>

                     <p>
                        All values displayed are income before taxes.
                    </p>
                </div>
