            <section>
                <h3>Mentimeter â€”</h3>

                <article class="grid-1-4">
                    <time>2020 â€” 2021</time>

                    <div>
                        <h4>Product Designer</h4>
                        <h5>48 000 SEK/month â†’ 49 000 SEK/month</h5>
                        <h5>~49 000 SEK/year occupational pension</h5>

                        <p>
                            When interviewing for Mentimeter, I got assigned a Frontend Dev take-home assignment by mistake. I don't normally do them as I think they are spec-work and do not provide value in evaluating designers (there is no collaboration or stakeholder management, which, IMO are key to work performance).
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            But the assignment was to create a <b>React</b>-based modular component as part of a hypothetical Design System, and I felt like even if I did not get the job, I would spend a week improving my code chops. I wrapped the assignment, sent it in, and waited for the eventual thanks for doing it, but we are going forward with another candidate.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Instead, I got a video call scheduled from <b>Niklas</b>, one of the founders and then CPO. The dev team was impressed with my exercise but very confused with a Designer who could write code. I was offered a Frontend Dev role, but I refused in favor of remaining a Product Designer, even if I would make the occasional PR. 
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            At Menti, I was finally able to do some real User Research. I also continued my path to becoming a Figma master, creating the missing component library to complete the <b>Ragnar Design System</b>, allowing the design team to create mockups and prototypes quickly that could be tested with users, saving us development time when the ideas did not work as planned. I also made several product improvements that remain to this day while proudly wearing the nickname "CSS Fairy" on my sleeve.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Unfortunately, around my year anniversary, we hired a new Design leader that wasn't so happy with my work and influence in the company. After trying for months to fix our relationship, I sadly concluded that I would need to move on for the sake of my mental health.
                        </p>
